# HTML popup management

# relace default values with full statement and adding unknown as a value. 
def htmlsex(sex): 
    
    if (sex == 'F'): 
        return 'female'
    elif (sex == 'M'):
        return 'male'
    else: 
        return 'unknown'
    
    
# Replacing the placeholders with full names races for help reading map 
def htmlrace(race): 
    
    if (race == 'A'): 
        return ' Asian '
    elif (race == 'B'): 
        return ' Black '
    elif (race == 'I'): 
        return ' American Indian '
    elif (race == 'W'): 
        return ' White '
    else: 
        return ' '
    
# adding information to the popup which betters reading the map
def htmlall(row): 
    
    html = '<center><p>' + \
            str(row['age']) + ' year old'+ htmlrace(row['race']) + htmlsex(row['sex']) + \
            '</br>' + \
            'Arrested: ' + str(row['arrestDate']) + ' ' + str(row['arrestTime']) + \
            '</br>' + \
            'Offense: ' + str(row['incidentOffense']) + \
            '</p></center>'
    return html

m1 = folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)

for idx, row in sample.iterrows():
    
    if (row['sex'] == 'M'): 
        folium.Marker(
            location=[row['lat'], row['long']],
            popup=htmlall(row),
            icon=folium.Icon(color='blue', icon='warning', prefix='fa')
        ).add_to(m1)
    elif (row['sex'] == 'F'):
        folium.Marker(
            location=[row['lat'], row['long']],
            popup=htmlall(row),
            icon=folium.Icon(color='pink', icon='warning', prefix='fa')
        ).add_to(m1)

Map 1: Map with markers indicating sex

Within the map I used markers that indicate the sex of the criminal/offender. As we can see, the majority of the offenses are commited by males. By viewing the map we estimate about 40-50 of these crimes are female led. Considering the sample sisze of 200, this is about 20% of the crimes being commited by females. This agrees with the public idea that most criminals are males. Historically, with our data, this is true. This is really important to understand that the subject of crimes being mostly male led is widely studied in a lot of fields, including but not limited to sociology, psychology, and feminist studies. The following map provides evidence that most crimes are led by male. There's an observable difference in rates between men and woman.

Map 2: markers including race

Beige = Asian, Black = Black, darkred = American Indian, White = white, blue = unknown

Within my second map I plot the crimes with markers that indicate race. This helps us conclude that factually black offenders make up the majority. Followed by white offenders. We can also analyze in our sample that we have one Asian offender which really sparks a conversation about if there is a relationship between crime and race. With census data from 2010, 72.4% of the US is white. and 12.6% of the US is black. In our sample these numbers are flipped with knowing that about 80% of our criminal offenders are black and 15% are white. Our major flaw in this is not accounting for interracial criminals. We as a population understand the growth in interracial marriage, but as a statistic where do those interracial offenders stand. They sort of fall through the cracks of our model. Although just by looking at the map we can try and make a connection between crime and race, but we should also understand that there is much more to it. There's other issues within these areas that are important to look into rather than race, such as poverty rates and homelessness.

Map 3: map with clustered markers indicating crime location

With our cluster markers we can find the common areas of crime easily in order to judge where the majority of crimes are done. On this map we can see that on the outside parts of baltimore we have much less crime, when we get towards the center of Baltimore, we get more and more crimes. The western side of Baltimore had the most crimes with 72. The Eastern side of Baltimore had the second highest with 55. The Northern part with 28 was second to last and the Southern part had 20. We can look further into certain areas to better understand. A popular area is John Hopkins Hospital. Where we see there's not many crimes near John Hopkins. There's about 5 to 10 crimes near the hospital. An error with this method is not being able to clearly see what region which cluster belongs to which. We use the folium method which gives us a shape of the region which helps. This map is incredibly helpful for people who are able to recognize areas in Baltimore, and are familiar with the city. They can easily interpret this information to knowing which areas are crime ridden and which others may not be. Rather than just saying East or West has most crime.

Map 4: Combination of the three map ideas above. Here, we have a map with location clusters, sex indicators, and race indicators. We use female/male sex symbols for icons on the markers as the sex indicators. We use yellow/black/green/grey/red (A/B/I/W/U) for colors of the markers as race indicators.

This map combines the ideas of all the maps from above. From this map, it seems like no matter the Baltimore region, the crimes are dominated by black males. In general, most crimes are committed by males, but when they are committed by females, they are usually black. On occasion, there is a white female. Actually, in this sample, there is an Asian female offender which is surprising because females have a lower criminal offense rate males and Asians are one of the racial groups with the lowest criminal offense rates. For further analysis, we could look into Baltimore demographics in order to get proportional numbers, rather than absolute numbers. For example, there may be more black persons committing crimes since the Baltimore population is heavily black. Thus, these are only our initial observations based on these interactive folium maps. Another future direction could be mapping and analyzing the specific offenses to see if the same offense could be related to a location or another feature.

Map 4: Combination of ideas

Here we combine all three previous ideas with location clusters, sex indicators, and race indicators. Using male and female sex symbols for icons on the markers are indicators of the criminals sex. And using colors for the markers as race indicators.

Combining all ideas can provide a better sense in analyzing the graphs information. Within the map it seems like in all baltimore regions the crime rates of black makes is incredibly high. Again we understand that most crime is commited by males an this confirms that. But it's important to note that when the crime is commited by a female they are highly likely black. An interesting point is the one which I stated earlier, with the sole Asian offender. This offender is not only the least likely race but also the least likely sex, being a woman. It's also important to understand that although the demographics of the crime is highly black. We must also know the demographics of the city. Knowing that a high percentage of the city residents are Black also helps in digesting the fact that the majority of the crimes are commited by blacks.

m4 = folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)
marker_cluster4 = MarkerCluster().add_to(m4)

for idx, row in sample.iterrows():
    sex = 'ok'
    raceColor='ok'
    if (row['sex'] == 'M'): 
        sex = 'mars'
    elif (row['sex'] == 'F'):
        sex = 'venus'
    
    if (row['race'] == 'A'):
        raceColor = 'beige'
    elif (row['race'] == 'B'):
        raceColor = 'black'
    elif (row['race'] == 'I'):
        raceColor = 'darkred'
    elif (row['race'] == 'W'):
        raceColor = 'white'    
    else:
        raceColor = 'blue'
        
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row['lat'], row['long']],
        popup=htmlall(row),
        icon=folium.Icon(color=raceColor, icon= sex, prefix='fa')
    ).add_to(marker_cluster4)
